03955nam a22005535i 9780226713502DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267135027 a10.7208/97802267135022doi  a(DE-B1597)523839  a(OCoLC)1058378444  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aB2430.R553 -- V5813 2009eb 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a236/.11 aRicoeur, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiving Up to Death /cPaul Ricoeur. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (132 p.) :b2 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tEditors’ Note -- tUp to Death Mourning and Cheerfulness -- tFragments -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen French philosopher Paul Ricoeur died in 2005, he bequeathed to the world a highly regarded, widely influential body of work which established him as one of the greatest thinkers of our time. He also left behind a number of unfinished projects that are gathered here and translated into English for the first time. Living Up to Death consists of one major essay and nine fragments. Composed in 1996, the essay is the kernel of an unrealized book on the subject of mortality. Likely inspired by his wife’s approaching death, it examines not one’s own passing but one’s experience of others dying. Ricoeur notes that when thinking about death the imagination is paramount, since we cannot truly experience our own passing. But those we leave behind do, and Ricoeur posits that the idea of life after death originated in the awareness of our own end posthumously resonating with our survivors. The fragments in this volume were written over the course of the last few months of Ricoeur’s life as his health failed, and they represent his very last work. They cover a range of topics, touching on biblical scholarship, the philosophy of language, and the idea of selfhood he first addressed in Oneself as Another. And while they contain numerous philosophical insights, these fragments are perhaps most significant for providing an invaluable look at Ricoeur’s mind at work. As poignant as it is perceptive, Living Up to Death is a moving testimony to Ricoeur’s willingness to confront his own mortality with serious questions, a touching insouciance, and hope for the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDeath. 0aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aAbel, Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldenstein, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPellauer, David.1 aSchlegel, Jean-Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226713502423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226713502.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles